  </widgets>
  <info><![CDATA[## WHAT IS IT?

This model demonstraits the effect of salt pollution on the growth of spotted salamanders and wood frogs. It affects factors such as survival rates, body size, and time to metamorphosis stages. It also demonstrates interspecies competition, genetic mutation, and statistical principles.

## HOW IT WORKS

When spawned in, amphibians will grow larger, metamorphosize, and potentially die, as time moves forward. The habitat they are born into, as well as whether or not other species are present, may affect these variables. Amphibians may also be born with color mutations. Numbers used for these variables in the code are based on several sttudies, cited below. 

## HOW TO USE IT

Begin by clicking start/reset button, and then click the buttons next to it to spawn in spotted salamanders, wood frogs, or both. This can be done multiple times for a larger sample size. Then click "one day," or other time based buttons continously and observe growth and death. Afterwards, click the "questions" buttons and read the command center, and click the "questions and answers" button when you have read and thought about the questions.

## THINGS TO TRY

The faster time buttons may be tempting, and they're useful for getting several data quickly, but try at least one round of progressing entirely through the "one day" button. 

Try the model at least three times, once with only salamanders, once with only frogs, and once with both. Pay attention to the survival rates each time. Try and remember and compare them, or write them down somewhere.

See how many blue or white animals you can get to survive to adulthood.

## EXTENDING THE MODEL

Wood frogs start as tadpoles, not eggs, because I did not find data on road salt effect on frog hatch time. There are no intermediate stages between larva and adult, again, because I could only find data on final metamorphosis time. 

Spotted salamander eggs and wood frog tadpoles only spawn in in groups of 100. This is not reflective of the studies, but rather exists to make percentages clearer to the user. Additionally, while interspecies competition is a factor in this model, intraspecies competition is not.

Only animal body length is measured, not body mass or snout-vent length, which the studies also had information on. The length of wood frogs does not change by interspecies competition, and uses Ocampo et al.'s data regardless. This is because Ocampo et al.'s findings were different from Sanzo & Hector's, and I did not want to confuse the user with data I did not fully understand. A second study supported the data of Ocampo et al. however it did not measure full body length, only snout vent length and mass (Hall et al., 2017)

Albino tadpoles only have a 1% chance of survival, as the literature I found suggested their survival odds are very low, but gave no clear numerical values. Amphibian adult wood frogs have been observed, however. Albino spotted salamander odds and axanthic wood frog odds were drawn from studies on populations of the same genus, but different species.

Ocampo et al. studied the factors of dragonfly larvae or zooplankton, and these findings were not incorporated as options.

If you have suggestions for expansions or find glitches, please email robinbrick119@gmail.com


## CREDITS AND REFERENCES

This model was created by Robin Brick, and she would like to thank Dr. Andrew Calinger-Yoak, for teaching her how to code in NetLogo, Ellie Nowels, for managing flowohio.org and adding this model to the website, and all of her beta testers: Andrew Calinger-Yoak, S. Conley, Ellen G, Ellie Nowels, Linda P, and Jenna Roller-Knapp.


Below is a bibliography of references from which data influenced the code

Hall, E. M., Brady, S. P., Mattheus, N. M., Earley, R. L., Diamond, M., & Crespi, E. J. (2017). Physiological consequences of exposure to salinized roadside ponds on wood frog larvae and adults. Biological Conservation, 209, 98-106.

Halls, K. M. (2004). Albino animals. Millbrook Press.

Henle, K., & Dubois, A. (2017). Studies on Anomalies in Natural Populations of Amphibians. MERTENSIELLA, 25, 185-242.

Mitchell, J. C., & Church, D. R. (2002). Leucistic marbled salamanders (Ambystoma opacum) in Virginia. Herpetological Review, 29, 229-230.

Ocampo, M., Chuirazzi, C., & Takahashi, M. K. (2022). The effects of road salt (NaCl), predation, and competition on the growth and community interactions of spotted salamanders (Ambystoma maculatum) and wood frogs (Lithobates sylvaticus). Environmental Pollution, 315, 120349.

Sanzo, D., & Hecnar, S. J. (2006). Effects of road de-icing salt (NaCl) on larval wood frogs (Rana sylvatica). Environmental pollution, 140(2), 247-256.
]]></info>
